It is often necessary to annotate a class, a class property, or methods, in Javascript you generally do it like this :<br />
<div style="color:Black;background-color:White;"><pre>
<span style="color:Blue;">function</span> myAnnotation(type, property) {
<span style="color:Green;">// do something</span>
}

<span style="color:Blue;">function</span> MyClass() {
}

myAnnotation(MyClass,<span style="color:#A31515;">&#39;myProperty&#39;</span>);

</pre></div>This often leads in bugs when you misspell 'myProperty'.<br />
In typescript you already define property in the class declaration, it could create a way to have a more concise syntax, and eliminates such bug to have a mechanism like this one :<br />
<div style="color:Black;background-color:White;"><pre>
<span style="color:Blue;">function</span> myAnnotation(type, property) {
}

<span style="color:Blue;">class</span> MyClass {
    @myAnnotation;
    myProperty:<span style="color:Blue;">string</span>;
}
</pre></div>
